<TITLE> SC upholds Khaleda bail in Niko case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 9 (bdnews24.com)The Supreme Court on Sunday upheld the bail BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia had secured from the High Court in Niko corruption case. A three-member Appellate Division bench headed by Chief Justice MM Ruhul Amin cancelled the leave to appeal filed by the AntiCorruption Commission challenging the High Court bail order. The court also ordered disposal of a writ petition in the regard. Khaleda secured bail from the High Court in Niko case on Sept 9, 2008. Barristers Rafique Ul Haque and Moudud Ahmed argued for Khaleda Zia and advocate Khurshid Alam Khan for the government at the hearing. Khan told bdnews24.com, "The court has rejected the leave to appeal petition as the case was not presented on behalf of the ACC. The court also ordered quick disposal of the writ petition filed in this regard." On July 30, the Appellate Division upheld the HC orders staying the Niko graft case proceedings. On that day, the ACC's appeal challenging the High Court orders was rejected. On July 9, 2008, the High Court stayed the proceedings of the Niko graft case filed against Khaleda. ACC assistant director Muhammad Mahbubul Alam filed the case on Dec 9, 2007 with Tejgaon Police Station against five persons including Khaleda. The allegation said the thew former prime minister and the others had caused the state to lose Tk 10, 000 crore through executing an oil and gas exploration treaty with Niko, a Canadian company. On May 5, the ACC submitted pressed charges in the court against 11 including Khaleda, putting the losses to the government exchequer at Tk 13, 777 crore. bdne
